1598":"10 August 1598","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1559":"1559","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fuller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a dresser of cloth, from Middle English <i>fuller</i> ‘fuller of cloth’ (partly from Old English <i>fullere</i>, partly from Old French <i>fouleor</i>, <i>foleur</i>, Latin <i>fullo</i>). Raw cloth had to be fulled, i.e. scoured, cleansed, and thickened by beating or trampling it in water, a process also known as <i>walking</i> or <i>tucking</i>, hence the surnames   Walker   and   Tucker   alongside <i>Fuller</i>. These three terms and surnames are characteristic of different parts of England. In general, in Middle English, <i>Fuller</i> is southern and eastern, while <i>Walker</i> belongs to the west and north and <i>Tucker</i> is southwestern. Compare   Fullen  .","English: variant of   Fullard   with loss of <i>-d</i>.","German (<b>Füller</b>): occupational name for a person whose work involved filling, such as a dauber, or a nickname for a gourmand or glutton. Compare   Filler  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walker","meanings":["English (mainly North and Midlands) and Scottish: occupational name for a fuller, from Middle English <i>walker</i>, Old English <i>wealcere</i> (an agent derivative of <i>wealcan</i> ‘to walk, tread’), ‘one who trampled cloth in a bath of lye or kneaded it, in order to strengthen it’. This was the regular term for the occupation during the Middle Ages in western and northern England. Compare   Fuller   and   Tucker  . As a Scottish surname it has also been used as a translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Fhucadair</b> ‘son of the fuller’. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","History: The name was brought to North America from northern England and Scotland independently by many different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. Samuel Walker came to Lynn, MA, <i>c.</i> 1630; Philip Walker was in Rehoboth, MA, in or before 1643. The surname was also established in VA before 1650; a Thomas Walker, born in 1715 in King and Queen County, VA, was a physician, soldier, and explorer."]},{"name":"Filler","meanings":["South German: occupational name for a flayer or skinner, from Middle High German <i>viller</i> ‘knacker’, from <i>villen</i> ‘to skin’.","Altered form of German <b>Füller</b> (see   Fuller  ).","English: variant of   Filer   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Fullen","meanings":["English: occupational name for a fuller (see   Fuller  ), from Old French <i>fulun</i> ‘fuller’.","English (Lancashire): branch of this family in Lancashire probably represents a variant of <b>Fulham</b> (see   Fullam  ), reintroduced from Ireland."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":25,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":34,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":45,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":61,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":63,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":96,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":118,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs John Fuller was born about 1524, in Norfolk, England. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with John Fuller."},"et":{"about 1524–":"umbes 1524–Surnud","1522–1559":"1522–1559","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Surnud","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1524–Female":"1524–Surnud","8 May 1599":"8. mai 1599","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"umbes 1549","1599":"1599","1522":"1522","about 1547":"umbes 1547","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1553":"1553","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","about 1524":"umbes 1524","10 August 1598":"10 august 1598","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1559":"1559","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Redenhall With Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England":"Redenhall with Harleston, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1524–":"noin 1524–Kuollut","1522–1559":"1522–1559","1547–1614":"1547–1614","1549–Female":"1549–Kuollut","1553–1599":"1553–1599","1524–Female":"1524–Kuollut","8 May 1599":"8. toukokuuta 1599","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1547":"1547","1524":"1524","about 1549":"noin 1549","1599":"1599","1522":"1522","about 1547":"noin 1547","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1553":"1553","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","about 1524":"noin 1524","10 August 1598":"10. elokuuta 1598","1549":"1549","1614":"1614","1559":"1559","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwi